issue.title: üêõWindows Defender marking cloudflared 2025.9.1 as Trojan:Win32/Kepavll!rfn

labels.name: Priority: Normal
labels.description: Minor issue impacting one or more users

issue.body:
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Install the cloudflared 2025.9.1 on Windows 11 with Defender.
2. Do a scan.
3. Executable will be marked as severe threat Trojan:Win32/Kepavll!rfn

**Environment and versions**
 - OS: Windows 11 24H2
 - Architecture: AMD64
 - Version: 2025.9.1

This behavious verified across different computers with different Defender (both consumer and corporate).

comment.body: Sudden positives in new releases reminds of how 3CX or SolarWinds got popped.   We need to know if this is being reviewed for legitimacy.

pull_request.title: fix: no version error on existing objecttemplates
pull_request.body:
<!-- If this PR is linked to a Jira ticket prefix your title with '[<PROJECT>-<KEY>]'-->
### Summary
<!-- Briefly describe what this PR accomplishes -->
<!-- Hint: If this resolves an issue include 'resolves #XXX' -->
Resolves https://issues.redhat.com/browse/PKO-323
This fix prevents PKO from throwing an error on older objecttemplates which don't have a `version` field in `status.controllerOf`.

Steps to verify:

1. Checkout a version PKO from before the bug was introduced (e.g `8af6f451fbc84919f77f7a66fc1f14673d1cd097`)
2. Deploy using the self-bootstrap-local job.
3. Create and object template.
4. Verify that is has no `version` in the  `.status.controllerOf` object.
5. Check this branch
6. Apply the self-bootstrap-local job to upgrade PKO
7. Verify that after reconciling `version` is added to the object templates `.status.controllerOf` field.

labels.name: size/M

labels.description: Indicates the PR's author has signed the DCO.

issue.body:
Hi maintainers,

This PR is ready for review. It addresses issue #3184 by adding a diagnostic step to the e2e test workflow that dumps redacted Secret YAMLs. This should help improve debuggability as discussed in the parent epic.

I have successfully run the full `./run-test.sh` suite locally, and all tests passed.

Please let me know if any changes are needed. Looking forward to your feedback!

Thanks.

comment.body: Hi @MikeSpreitzer, thanks so much for the detailed review! I've updated the script to use jq as you suggested and also fixed the commit message to resolve the failing check. The new approach is much cleaner. Please let me know if there's anything else.
